{{notability|date=July 2011}}
'''Women to the Top''' ('''W2T''') was a European project for bringing more women into top management.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/ekonomi/lika-villkor-pa-jobbet-viktigt/|title=Lika villkor på jobbet viktigt|last=Björklund|first=Marianne|date=2004-11-08|work=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-02-06}}</ref> It was funded by the [[European Commission]] and ran 2003-2005 in Estonia, Denmark, Greece and Sweden,<ref name="aboutus">{{cite web|url=http://www.w2t.se/uk/about.htm|title=Women to the Top|publisher=Women to the Top (W2T) |accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> culminating in a transnational conference in Stockholm, 24–25 January 2005.<ref name=FinalReport/> The total budget was 5.6 million [[Swedish krona|SEK]] (half a million euros). The project was directed toward private and public employers.<ref name="svd">{{cite news|url=http://www.svd.se/naringsliv/nyheter/artikel_1043415.svd|title=Gemensamt krafttag för ett mer jämställt Europa|last=Danielsson|first=Anna|date=2005-01-25|work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-02-06}}</ref>
The final report of Women to the Top, and a summary of the final report, are available online<ref name=FinalReport>{{cite web|last1=Trollvik|first1=Marie|title=Women to the Top (Final Report)|url=http://www.femtech.at/fileadmin/downloads/Wissen/Themen/Gleichstellung_in_Unternehmen/Women_to_the_top.pdf|publisher=FEMtech - Frauen in Forschung und Technologie|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=FinalReportSummary>{{cite web|title=Final Report - Women to the Top (Summary)|url=http://www.w2t.se/uk/facts/final_report.htm|publisher=Women to the Top|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> and an article was published discussing the results: {{cite journal|last=Eriksson-Zetterquist|first=Ulla|author2=Styhre, Alexander |year=2007|title=Overcoming the Glass Barriers: Reflection and Action in the 'Women to the Top' Programme|journal=Gender, Work & Organization|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|volume=15|issue=2|pages=133–160|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0432.2007.00366.x}}
== Estonia == In Estonia, Tiina Raitviir surveyed female executives from Estonia’s Top500 companies. One hundred women managers were identified as the basis for an informal network and a mentorship program. Eighty women managers participated in an initial seminar. Nine women followed up in subsequent workshops.<ref name=FinalReport/> All of the companies were foreign owned because it was believed they would be more willing to participate in the project than Estonian companies.<ref name="svd" />
== Denmark == Fifty-one potential top managers attended interdisciplinary networks hosted by CeLi and two trade unions, the Danish Society of Engineers (IDA) and the Danish Association of Lawyers and Economists (DJØF). These women formed professional networks for Women in Top Management, Women in Human Resource Management and Women in Project Management. They attended seminars and a national conference.<ref name=FinalReport/> In addition, four recruitment firms were involved in a focus group to develop gender recommendations for consultants and managers.<ref name=FinalReport/>
== Greece == In Greece, the project worked with The Research Centre for Gender Equality (KETHI). Thirty women attended counselling on entrepreneurship for women who wanted to start their own businesses. Seven more women attended vocational workshops at the organisations Amel, Elgeka and the Municipality of Athens. Members from ten recruitment companies took part in seminars and research on gender inequality and leadership. A survey was carried out to learn more about gender and employment.<ref name=FinalReport/>
== Sweden == In Sweden the project was administered by the [[Swedish Ombudsman for Equal Opportunities|Ombudsman for Equal Opportunities]] (Jämo)<ref name="NIKK">{{Cite news | last = Westlund | first = Jennie | title = Kvinnor på toppen ingen quick-fix | magazine = NIKK Magasin | issn =1502-1521 | publisher = [[NIKK]] | issue = 1.08 | pages = 18–19 | year = 2008 | language = Swedish | url=http://issuu.com/nikk---nordic-gender-institute/docs/nikkmagasin_1-2008/10 | accessdate=2009-02-06}}</ref> with Marie Trollvik as project leader.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/ekonomi/manligt-natverk-viktigast-for-kvinnlig-karriar/|title=Manligt nätverk viktigast för kvinnlig karriär|last=Björklund|first=Marianne|author2=Koblanck, Anna |date=2004-02-02|work=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-02-06}}</ref> Fifteen major Swedish companies were involved, both public and private, and set up networks and a mentorship program. The project was evaluated by Jämo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w2t.se/se/filer/JamOs_uppfoljning_av_Women_to_the_Top.pdf|title=Women to the top - 14 arbetsgivares erfarenheter och åtgärder för att rekrytera fler kvinnor till chefspositioner|date=September 2007|publisher=[[Swedish Ombudsman for Equal Opportunities]]|language=Swedish| accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> and the [[School of Business, Economics and Law]] at the [[University of Gothenburg]].<ref name="gu">{{Cite book | last =Renemark | first =David | publication-date =2007-10-19 | title =Steg på vägen till toppen - Utvärdering av arbetet efter projektet Women to the top | series =GRI-rapport | publisher =[[School of Business, Economics and Law]] at the [[University of Gothenburg]] | issue =2007:2 | hdl =2077/7446 | issn =1400-4801 | language =Swedish }}</ref>
